	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=1854'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#339999;font-weight:bold; '>Skrax_Swifttail</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Defender<br>
			
				Posts: 1305<br>
				
				Registered: 03-02-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=1854'>







<img src="/eq/i/icons/Classes/monk.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&message.id=142650#M142650">17</a> of 59
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1284 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Elizor-LS wrote:<BR>
<DIV>Yesterday, while kicking around suggestions to "fix" EQ before it up and dies on us, a player posting on Mobhunter&nbsp;under the name of Braxis tossed out a suggestion to segragate the players to different servers by level.&nbsp; After playing with this idea some, I believe it would be a lot of work, but have the potential to&nbsp; address a huge number of problems in the game, both social and structural.&nbsp; Because it would be a huge post to outline this plan in a single message, I am breaking it into two parts, this one being the general outline and the other is the specifics.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The way this would work is that each server would be assigned to a tier (a group of levels). All characters in the game would be moved, for free, to the server for their appropriate level.&nbsp;&nbsp;<FONT color=#ffffff>&nbsp;Most importantly, the reduced number of servers available to each&nbsp;tier of&nbsp;characters guarantees a higher player density.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Whenever a character reaches the maximum level for that tier, their xp becomes "soft-capped."&nbsp; They can earn xp up to the next level (if they wish to stay on the server) but they cannot advance to that level unless they leave for the next tier.&nbsp; Transfer to a higher tier server is free, and the player indicates their choice via /movelog.&nbsp; Limit is still 8 characters per server, but now your true maximum# of characters at high level is # of top-tier servers times 8, rather than total number of servers times 8 (advantage: SOE database!).&nbsp; Presumably, there would be 2-4 newbie tier servers, an equal, perhaps slightly greater number of mid-tier servers, and unlimited number of high tier servers, as necessary.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffffff>For lower level characters, all of their armor and weapons would be flagged NO DROP at the time of the transfer, to prevent hording of twink gear.&nbsp; No inventory can be transferred, and only limited plat.</FONT>&nbsp; <EM>(Alternately, limit each character to a single weapon and piece of armor, both flagged no drop. Or for simplicity &amp; no database changes each character gets a "standard gear package" and all their actual items are deleted.)</EM><FONT color=#ffffff>&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT>Looking at the lowest level, this means that the first generation of characters will probably be heavily twinked (unless the more restrictive options are selected), but since all their gear becomes no drop upon move, the economy will not be directly affected in the long run.&nbsp; Limits on inventory transfer from the current servers and (optionally) a tradeskill cap can prevent flooding with high level smithed or tailored gear.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ffffff>Eventually the econonmy will stabilize around level-appropriate gear, because the lower tier servers have no uber lvl 70's to farm twink gear.&nbsp; </DIV></FONT>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Socialogically, guilds on the low-tier servers will be able to focus on events and players within their own levels. <FONT color=#ffffff>There will be decreased social strain from guilds that have divided into "high-end" and "low-end" players.&nbsp; This will be replaced by cross-server ties and recruiting;&nbsp;now a guild is one or the other by design.&nbsp;</FONT>&nbsp;High end guilds that want to guarantee a fresh stream of replacements will forge ties with guilds on lower level servers (or even found junior chapters there.)&nbsp; Thus it becomes possible for players at the top and bottom of the game to have a common or at least associated guild community, yet still focus on their own levels.&nbsp; Perma-newbies, or players who don't value the high end game can stay at whatever level they desire for as long as they choose to do so.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffffff>VERY IMPORTANT:&nbsp; Future expansions can (indeed, must) offer something to all levels, so that each tier gets at least one new zone, new quests, items, etc.&nbsp; Care must be taken at the lowest levels to prevent mudflation; even if this eventually means no new items for those levels.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff00>Advantages:</FONT> Non-mudflated economy at lowest levels, even playing field (no twinking), higher player density, greater socialization.&nbsp; Lower hardware requirement on newbie servers (not all zones needed).&nbsp; No further zone redesigns needed (i.e. end elimination of lowbie dungeons).&nbsp; Game design no longer needs to worry about mixing very different levels.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff00>Disadvantages: </FONT>No mules or bazaar alts. No twinking or powerleveling <EM>(Well, some will consider&nbsp;that a disadvantage!)</EM> Quest disruption--redesign of some will be required.&nbsp; Slowed advancement for those who just want to level a new character to raid level.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Each of the disadvantages can be designed around eventually.&nbsp; Knowing&nbsp;SOE, the solutions&nbsp;would be part of a future expansion, so you'd have to buy it... :-)&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>In the next posting, I'll get into the specifics of each tier, and&nbsp;their limits.&nbsp; See you in about an hour...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<P>Have to say that I'm thinking this is a horrible idea.&nbsp; You can write it up any way you want, but there is no reason to seperate the levels.&nbsp; I'd go into the many details, but Ice and others stated them pretty clearly.</FONT></P>
<P>Try to justify it any way you want, but this is a bad solution to a situation that doesn't yet require a solution.</FONT></P>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=670542">Brother Skrax Swifttail</a><br><a href="http://www.scriptedlegacy.net/">Stone Fist on Fennin Ro</a><br><a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&message.id=6162">Monk of Happiness</a>
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
		<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
		 <span class=date_text>12-22-2004</span> <span class=time_text>09:50 AM</span>
		</span>
		</td>

		
