			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=11797'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&message.id=142671#M142671">25</a> of 59
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1215 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			I actually suggested something to that tune in another thread, and responces were positive. However, the suggested system was far more flexible.<br><br>Here is my system as envisioned:<br>Available options for character creation are:<br>1. The usual way:<br>Create on a regular server, name unique to that server, counts towards slot limit on that server, and character starts on that server. Can access shared bank, can be twinked, PLed, whatever. You know, what we have now.<br><br>2. The 'I know where I want to end up' way:<br>Create on a regular server, name unique to that server, counts towards slot limit on that server. However, player shooses to start out on a 'newbie' server. If someone on newbie server has that name already, an 'x' is added. When player feels it is time to go to a regular server, the origin server is the only allowed one. Shared bank links only banks of characters that exist on same server. This character can be invited into a guild on originating server, and participate in guildchat. The guild tag will be &lt;server-guildname&gt;<br><br>3. The 'I have no goal yet' way:<br>Character created directly on a 'newbie' server. Name unique to newbie server, not reserved on any other server. Counts towards slot limit on newbie server itself. When player decides to move to a regular server, he can choose any server. Of course, name collision issues are treated as with any regular server transfer.<br><br>A newbie server differs from a regular server in one way: cannot level above say, 35. All content is there. Surely, level restrited stuff sits unused, so I guess planes and such can be turned off. But if someone gets a kick out of streaking naked through Maiden's Eye at level 20, why not? I certainly got thrills making a Felwithe-Erudin trip at level 5 (this was before Kunark came out). About only content difference would be to return all revamped dungeons (CT, MMC, SP, Hole, Nurga, Droga) to their original states. Bazaar, PoK, Nexus - all there. No tradeskill restriction.<br><br>Original suggestion only considered newbie server, but mid-level server might be a good idea too, since midlevel population seems to be even more sparse, and grouping need at mid-level is higher.<br><br>Any character on newbie server can at any point be transferred to any of the regular servers (final move), or to a mid-level server. I am not sure if mid-level server should have lower level boundary, I think something like lvl 25 minimum would be good. On midlevels server, one cannot level past say, 54 (55 opens access to Valor/Storms/ Torment/CoD, these are not really viable for an all-55 group).<br><br>Summary:<br>Anyone lvl 1-24 on newbie can do a free one-way transfer to regular server.<br>Anyone 25-35 on newbie can move one-way free to regular or midlevel.<br>Anyone 25-54 on midlevel can at any moment move one-way free to regular.<br><br>Transfers are fulll items/plat. Shared bank stays behind, though. Better empty it out before moving your last character off newbie or midlevel.<br><br>Thoughts on this one?	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
